maskRangeR; improving spatial and temporal accuracy of species distribution models

Cory Merow, Peter J. Galante, Cecina Babich Morrow, Jamie M. Kass, Alex Moore, Jorge Velasquez, Robert P. Anderson, Mary E. Blair

2019-02-22

International Space Station (NASA)

About

The Group on Earth Observation Biodiversity Observation Network (GEO BON) BON in a Box Initiative enables more effective policy responses to changes in biodiversity by creating tools and platforms that implement advanced methods for biodiversity observation systems. It rectifies a disconnect between academic communities and those of conservation practitioners and decision-makers in understanding and implementing best practices and state-of-the-art methods. Nevertheless, methods for biodiversity models are continuously advancing, especially via open-source code-based analyses that are difficult to implement. Hence, there is a pressing need for user-friendly open-source software that is interactive and flexible, provides conceptual and methodological guidance, features an expandable framework, and affords transparency and reproducibility. The paucity of such tools hinders scientific exploration and discussion among a broad user base that includes policymakers, practitioners, scientists and academics.

The goal of the project Expanding Wallace Modeling Software to Support Biodiversity Change Indicator Calculations for GEO BON Assessment and Reporting is to expand the open-source software Wallace as a tool for BON in a Box that will facilitate assessment of biodiversity change indicators for GEO BON assessment and reporting. The project objectives are to:

  1. Develop two new R packages to calculate biodiversity change indicators using NASA Earth Science data and add them to Wallace as modules.

  2. Integrate Wallace with BioModelos, an existing BON in a Box tool developed for the Colombia Biodiversity Observation Network (BON).

  3. Create interactive web-based training and workshop materials on best practices for using SDMs to contribute to biodiversity change indicator assessments for resource management and conservation decision-making.

R packages

(1) maskRangeR

In addition to other masking functionalities, maskRangeR spatiotemporally matches in-situ observations of a species’ occurrence to remote sensing (e.g. MODIS-derived) products to estimate species’ environmental tolerances, and use them to refine models of species’ niches and estimate the species’ current distribution, e.g. accounting for land cover change (the Essential Biodiversity Variable, EBV “species distribution”).

(2) The second R package will aggregate individual models of species’ niches and distributions (e.g., the products of maskRangeR) for calculation of biodiversity indicators and their change over time. Indicators will be determined in consultation with our international partners but will likely include: extent of occurrence, percent suitable land cover, mean human footprint, protected area coverage and representativeness, recent trends, and projected trends.

Integration with BioModelos

BioModelos is a BON-in-a-box tool for Colombia’s BON. It helps connect biodiversity experts with data and tools. Through facilitating the curation of occurrence records, editing models, identifying suitable ecological variables and assisting in model approval, BioModelos is the bridge between expert modeling and expert (taxonomic) knowledge. Conservation practitioners can access important model statistics (indicators of biodiversity and ecosystem services) such as: extent of occurrence, proportion of range under protected status, and projected change in future scenarios.

Training materials

The team for this NASA grant will also develop training materials and best practices for modeling species’ niches and distributions in biodiversity change indicator assessments for the expanded Wallace in both English and Spanish. Materials will be web-based and openly available. They will be available as both guidance text within Wallace and also published as part of an open source teaching module for the Center for Biodiversity and Conservation at the American Museum of Natural History (CBC-AMNH) Network of Conservation Educators and Practitioners (NCEP). NCEP is a global initiative that seeks to improve the availability and quality of conservation education and professional training.
